"The first public school building in Ottumwa was built in 1865 on College Square, which had been set apart for educational purposes when the city was laid out. Later known as Adams School, the first building was torn down and replaced by this structure in 1883... the March 17,1933 fire started as workmen repairing the roof used soldering tools. The destroyed roof was replaced and Adams School continued to serve the community for many more years before being torn down."

"Established in 1864 by George Haw, Haw Hardware was twice destroyed by fire. After the 1886 fire...the business moved several times before settling in this location at 106-108 West Main Street. The building burned in October 1913 along with a large chunk of downtown Ottumwa, leaving only the wreckage pictured above."
On October 1st, 1960 a fire destroyed Marshall Auto. State investigators believed the fire to be suspicious and carried out an investigation into fire.

"The meatpacking firm of Morrell & Company, headquartered in Ottumwa since 1877, was nearly destroyed by fire on July 12,1893...The Morrell plant was a major employer until closing almost exactly eighty years later in July, 1973."

On November 16th, 1940 a fire started in Ottumwa City Hall. The building was ultimately saved but the fire permanently damaged the integrity of the building and a decade later a new city hall was built.
